되요? 돼요!

Dictionary form: 되다
되 + 어 = 돼 (ㅚ + ㅓ = ㅙ)
as in
되+어(요). = 돼(요).
되+었어(요). = 됐어(요).

TIPS:
Is it at the end of a sentence in present or past tense with ~어(요) and ~었어(요)?
👉 Use 돼 : comebination of 되+어 

When the stem 되 combines with endings that don’t start with ~어, DO NOT change it to 돼.
되+고 = 되고
되+지만 = 되지만
되+는데 = 되는데
되+(으)ㄹ 거예요 = 될 거예요.
되+(스)ㅂ니다 = 됩니다.
되+(느)ㄴ다 = 된다.

#되vs돼 #돼요 #되요vs돼요 #되다

#koreanculture (can we cal this culture? 😅)

“I learned Hangeul. What next?”

We all studied English. The core step in English is to learn to talk and think in the correct word order: Subject - Verb - Object.

Korean has more freedom in terms of the word order and omission of subject and object as long as you say verb and adjective at the end.

1. Just say a verb and adjective. That’s a sentence.
2. You cannot use dictionary form.
3. Learn the most useful and basic verb/adjective ending so that you can make a sentence.
4. If you don’t know how to change the dictionary form to sentence endings, you can’t say anything in Korean.
👉 Learn ~어요/아요 sentence ending: also called present tense!

The mystery of Korean you

그대: song lyrics, poetry
당신: spouse (old fashioned), picking a fight, unidentified audience (Tweet)
너: close friends who are the same age or younger

👉 What do I use then?
Who they are! Their identities and their relationship to you!!! 
- name + 씨
- their position (선생님, 대표님, 사장님)
- their relationship to you (언니/누나, 오빠/형, 엄마)

Escaping the cold and gloomy winter weather, we traveled to a Cancun all-inclusive resort.

멕시코도 처음이고, 올인클루시브도 처음 가 봤는데 푹 쉬다가 오기 좋더라구요. 
It was first time to be in Mexico and at an all-inclusive resort: it was great to take a full rest.

나흘 동안 책 읽고 수영하고 먹고 자고 마시고 열심히 쉬고 왔어요. 
For 4 days, I read books and swam and ate and slept and drank and rested with all my heart.

4월 말까지 수업이랑 클래스101 강의 제작으로 엄청 바쁠 예정이라서 일부러 노트북도 안 가져가고 제대로 쉬었어요. 
I’m scheduled to be extremely busy with online classes and producing CLASS101 lectures, so I didn’t take my laptop with me to take a complete rest.

I’m back with @ttmik’s @ever4one to help you get a feel of the honorific ending 세요 and its past tense 셨어요! in comparison with the casual ending 야 or 아/어. 

반말 (casual)
👉 Noun(이)야 : question words are nouns too!
- 어디야? Where is it / where are you?
- 뭐야? What is it?
- 누구야? Who is it?
- 선물이야. It’s a gift.
- 나야. It’s me.

👉 VERB(ADJ)~아/어 
- 뭐 해? What are you doing?
- 뭐 했어? What did you do?
- 잘 지내? Are you doing well?
- 잘 지냈어? Have you been well?
- 밥 먹었어? Did you eat?

높임말 (honorific ending)
👉 Present: ~(으)세요
👉 Past: ~(으)셨어요

How polite is polite enough in Korean? 

고맙습니다 : most polite and formal form of the native word 고맙다(to be thankful)

감사합니다 : most polite and formal form of the sino word 감사하다 (to thank, to be thankful)

👉 Generally speaking, traditionally the sino-words are used more in official, formal, and honorific ways.

👉 감사합니다 is not inherently more polite than 고맙습니다: however, in speakers’ language use, 감사합니다 is used to be more polite and humble.

➕감사드립니다 
The sino-word 감사(gratitude) is combined with the humble form of the verb 주다(to give)
= Very humble and polite expression

👉 You can also use it a bit more casually while keeping the humbleness by changing the sentence ending to ~아/어요: 감사드려요.

Don’t you just love how Netflix translates when people want to drop the polite ending? Here’s how you can suggest dropping the polite ending to native speakers!

1. You are the younger one:
말씀 놓으세요. “Please put down your words.”
말씀 편하게 하세요. “Please speak comfortably.”
👉 Culturally, younger ones will suggest the older one drop the politeness as courtesy so that the older one can talk to you comfortably.

2. You are the older one:
말 놔도 돼요? ”Is it okay if I put down the words?”
말 편하게 해도 돼요? “Is it okay to talk comfortably?”
👉 You can use this to suggest to someone at the same age! Another ending you can use to suggest is 말 놓을까요?, 말 편하게 할까요?
